--- In archive-crawler@yahoogroups.com, &quot;Gordon Mohr&quot; &lt;gojomo@a...&gt; 
wrote:
&gt; Other interesting notes about this crawl, having pored over the 
&gt; output logs:
&gt; 
&gt; * There were no &quot;internal error&quot; results -- that is, unexpected
&gt;   Java exceptions due to buggy code or deep I/O strangeness. 
&gt;   My smaller development machine text crawls, on Windows XP, almost 
&gt;   always have a handful of these, so the Linux IBM JVM/runtime
&gt;   classes seems to exhibit less flakiness than the Sun Windows JVM/
&gt;   runtime. 
&gt; 
&gt; * 709 problematic discovered URIs were logged. Most of these were
&gt;   &quot;mailto&quot;s, which aren&#39;t yet being treated separately from other
&gt;   URI types, and are especially likely to choke the java.net.URI
&gt;   parser. Of the other 183, all appeared to be genuinely illegal
&gt;   URIs. In a few cases, we might want to tolerate/patch-up the 
&gt;   page author&#39;s error to match the toleration/patching that browsers
&gt;   do; I&#39;m working on such fixes to our extractor.
&gt; 
&gt; - Gordon
