&gt; 
&gt; &gt; I started a Heritrix crawl of our first 8 test hosts early Sunday 
&gt; &gt; morning. 
&gt; &gt; 
&gt; &gt; Some initial results:
&gt; &gt; 
&gt; &gt; - In 24 hours, it had successfully downloaded over 79,000 URIs. 
&gt; &gt; 
&gt; &gt; - Memory footprint was under 400MBs at this time -- indicating 
&gt; &gt;   that with a similarly-constrained focused crawl we&#39;re likely
&gt; &gt;   to be able to crawl 320,000+ URIs before exhausting the current
&gt; &gt;   RAM-based structures. 
&gt; &gt; 
&gt; &gt; - At the end of 24 hours, it was only fetching from two of the
&gt; &gt;   sites -- match.com and city.fi -- just as with Mercator and
&gt; &gt;   HTTrack towards the end of their runs. 
&gt; &gt; 
&gt; &gt; - At 24 hours, it encountered a bug that halted its useful
&gt; &gt;   fetching: while we&#39;re properly expiring IP info, we have
&gt; &gt;   no facility for doing a fresh DNS lookup. (The &quot;dns:&quot; URI
&gt; &gt;   is considered already-fetched, and thus will not be 
&gt; &gt;   fetched again.) So from the 24-hour mark on, the logs show
&gt; &gt;   only &quot;unable to fetch because a prerequisite is unavailable&quot;
&gt; &gt;   errors. 
&gt; &gt; 
&gt; &gt; Another bug noted: our timestamp-writing routine is using
&gt; &gt; 12-hour based times, so 11:59pm is showing as 1159 rather than 
&gt; &gt; 2359, and 12:59am is showing as 1259 rather than 0059.
&gt; &gt; 
&gt; &gt; The logs and ARCs for comparison against Mercator and HTTrack
&gt; &gt; are available on crawl09:/0/crawls/test-gojomo/8hosts/
&gt; &gt; 
